And we don't get away with just ignoring it.

59
00:02:20,780 --> 00:02:21,800
What's the difference?

60
00:02:21,800 --> 00:02:22,420
First of all,

61
00:02:22,420 --> 00:02:24,640
I'll tell you what the basic difference is

62
00:02:24,640 --> 00:02:25,880
in classical physics and in quantum mechanics.

63
00:02:25,900 --> 00:02:29,080
In classical physics,

64
00:02:29,080 --> 00:02:32,060
measurements can be arbitrarily gentle.

65
00:02:33,300 --> 00:02:36,160
Arbitrarily gentle means that you can find out

66
00:02:36,160 --> 00:02:39,020
anything that you want about a system in principle

67
00:02:39,660 --> 00:02:44,130
by interacting with it with something that changes

68
00:02:44,130 --> 00:02:48,600
anything about it by an arbitrarily small amount.

69
00:02:49,380 --> 00:02:50,460
For example,

70
00:02:50,460 --> 00:02:52,230
you want to locate the location

71
00:02:52,230 --> 00:02:54,000
of a particle in classical physics.

72
00:02:54,340 --> 00:02:55,560
How do you do it?

73
00:02:55,560 --> 00:02:57,000
You shine some light on it.

74
00:02:57,180 --> 00:02:58,980
You shine some light on it,

75
00:02:58,980 --> 00:03:00,120
and you make an image.

76
00:03:00,900 --> 00:03:01,740
Of course,

77
00:03:01,740 --> 00:03:04,300
you have to use light which is small

78
00:03:04,300 --> 00:03:06,860
enough wavelength that it can resolve the object.

79
00:03:07,340 --> 00:03:08,020
This is true,

80
00:03:08,020 --> 00:03:13,100
but there's no limit to how weak a

81
00:03:13,100 --> 00:03:18,180
light signal can be at a given wavelength.

82
00:03:18,820 --> 00:03:21,620
You can make the light signal as weak as you

83
00:03:21,620 --> 00:03:24,420
like so that it carries as little energy as you like.

84
00:03:25,840 --> 00:03:27,640
As little momentum as you like.

85
00:03:28,100 --> 00:03:30,740
Let it interact with the thing you're interested in.

86
00:03:31,260 --> 00:03:32,480
Form an image,

87
00:03:32,480 --> 00:03:35,840
and then after that image has been formed,

88
00:03:35,840 --> 00:03:38,380
it can be magnified.

89
00:03:38,540 --> 00:03:40,700
Not magnified in the sense of making it bigger,

90
00:03:40,700 --> 00:03:43,080
but what's the right word for amplified?

91
00:03:43,560 --> 00:03:44,520
It can be amplified.

92
00:03:45,120 --> 00:03:48,950
And so the experiment itself can be arbitrarily gentle and still

93
00:03:48,950 --> 00:03:52,780
find out anything you might want to know about the system.

94
00:03:52,780 --> 00:03:57,210
The result of that is an experiment can always

95
00:03:57,210 --> 00:04:01,640
be done which has no effect whatever on future experiments,

96
00:04:01,740 --> 00:04:03,660
on subsequent experiments done,

97
00:04:03,660 --> 00:04:04,240
for example,

98
00:04:04,240 --> 00:04:04,960
right afterwards.

99
00:04:06,080 --> 00:04:07,700
That's classical physics.

100
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:09,900
Quantum physics is not like that.

101
00:04:10,060 --> 00:04:12,890
Quantum physics is such

102
00:04:12,890 --> 00:04:15,720
that experiments inevitably change systems.

103
00:04:17,079 --> 00:04:19,920
Any experiment to measure

104
00:04:19,920 --> 00:04:22,760
something will change something else.

105
00:04:23,480 --> 00:04:26,890
It's almost as though the experiment to measure coins

106
00:04:26,890 --> 00:04:30,300
